---
import PageFrame from '../layouts/PageFrame.astro';

const comparisons = [
  {
    name: 'APM suites',
    base: 'Datadog, Dynatrace, New Relic, and similar platforms',
    differs: [
      'APMs instrument your frameworks and measure spans continuously. jvmguard records only the transactions you define.',
      'APMs gather application and end-user data and send it to a cloud backend. jvmguard runs behind your firewall.',
      'jvmguard is a complement, not a replacement. APMs give you breadth and alerting, jvmguard gives you deep, targeted captures.',
    ],
  },
  {
    name: 'Continuous profilers',
    base: 'Grafana Pyroscope, Parca and Polar Signals, Elastic Universal Profiling',
    differs: [
      'Continuous profilers sample broadly and never stop. jvmguard captures a deep artifact, a heap dump or a JFR recording, from the one JVM that needs it, only when warranted.',
      'The overhead trade-offs are different. jvmguard stays near-zero in steady state and captures depth only when warranted.',
      'Captures are standard JFR and HPROF, ready to open in JProfiler, JMC, or Eclipse MAT.',
    ],
  },
  {
    name: 'Plain JFR and jcmd',
    base: 'Built into the JDK. JFR recordings, jcmd operations, and JDK Mission Control for analysis.',
    differs: [
      'Without jvmguard, getting a heap dump means SSH access to the production host, running jcmd by hand, and transferring the file. In most organizations, developers do not have that access.',
      'jvmguard replaces the SSH workflow with authorized, audited access. A profiler-role user starts a capture from the UI or via a coding agent. Every action is audited.',
      'One trigger fires across all matching JVMs in the fleet, not one-by-one over individual JVMs.',
    ],
  },
];
---

<PageFrame
  active="compare"
  title={`How jvmguard compares`}
  description="How jvmguard compares to APMs, continuous profilers and JFR and jcmd."
>
  <section class="shell hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">Comparison</p>
    <h1>How jvmguard compares</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      jvmguard captures deep JVM profiles only when something warrants it, and only with authorization
      and an audit trail. Here is how that differs from the tools you may already run.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="shell">
    <div class="rule">
      <span class="rule__no">§ 01</span>
      <span class="rule__label">Adjacent approaches</span>
    </div>
    <div class="cmp">
      {comparisons.map((c) => (
        <article class="cmp__row">
          <header class="cmp__head">
            <h2>{c.name}</h2>
            <p class="muted">{c.base}</p>
          </header>
          <ul class="cmp__diff">
            {c.differs.map((d) => (
              <li>{d}</li>
            ))}
          </ul>
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="shell">
    <div class="rule">
      <span class="rule__no">§ 02</span>
      <span class="rule__label">What jvmguard is not</span>
    </div>
    <div class="panel isnot">
      <p>
        jvmguard is not an APM. There is no continuous tracing, no distributed trace export, and no
        metrics pipeline, and it does not auto-instrument your frameworks. It records only the
        lightweight telemetries and the transactions you define, so steady-state overhead stays near
        zero. Deep captures are intentional and scoped, and they stay on your infrastructure. No user
        data is exported to a remote backend.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="shell">
    <div class="rule">
      <span class="rule__no">§ 03</span>
      <span class="rule__label">Where jvmguard fits</span>
    </div>
    <div class="panel fits">
      <div class="fits__item">
        <svg class="fits__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24" height="24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M20 13c0 5-3.5 7.5-7.66 8.95a1 1 0 0 1-.67-.01C7.5 20.5 4 18 4 13V6a1 1 0 0 1 1-1c2 0 4.5-1.2 6.24-2.72a1.17 1.17 0 0 1 1.52 0C14.51 3.81 17 5 19 5a1 1 0 0 1 1 1z"/><path d="m9 12 2 2 4-4"/></svg>
        <p>
          A developer gets a deep capture from a production JVM through authorized, audited access,
          without an SSH session on the host.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="fits__item">
        <svg class="fits__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24" height="24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><rect width="16" height="12" x="4" y="8" rx="2"/><path d="M12 8V4"/><path d="M2 14h2"/><path d="M20 14h2"/><path d="M15 13v2"/><path d="M9 13v2"/></svg>
        <p>
          An AI agent operates on production JVMs within scope and rate limits, and every operation is
          written to a SIEM-compatible audit log.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="fits__item">
        <svg class="fits__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24" height="24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M22 12h-2.48a2 2 0 0 0-1.93 1.46l-2.35 8.36a.25.25 0 0 1-.48 0L9.24 2.18a.25.25 0 0 0-.48 0l-2.35 8.36A2 2 0 0 1 4.49 12H2"/></svg>
        <p>
          Lightweight always-on monitoring triggers a capture automatically when a threshold is
          crossed.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</PageFrame>

<style>
  .hero {
    padding-top: var(--space-7);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-5);
  }
  .cmp {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0;
  }
  .cmp__row {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--rule-strong);
    padding-block: var(--space-5);
  }
  @media (min-width: 820px) {
    .cmp__row {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr 1.4fr;
      gap: var(--space-6);
    }
  }
  .cmp__head h2 {
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-2);
    font-size: var(--step-2);
  }
  .cmp__head p {
    margin: 0;
  }
  .cmp__diff {
    margin: 0;
    padding-left: 1.1rem;
    max-width: none;
  }
  .cmp__diff li {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }
  .isnot h3 {
    color: var(--brand-deep);
  }
  .grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-4);
  }
  @media (min-width: 820px) {
    .grid--3 {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    }
  }
  .fits__item {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    align-items: flex-start;
  }
  .fits__item + .fits__item {
    margin-top: var(--space-4);
  }
  .fits__icon {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    color: var(--brand);
    margin-top: 0.2rem;
  }
  .fits__item p {
    margin: 0;
    max-width: none;
  }
 </style>
